THOUGHT: The new failure indicates the cost model’s Scalars map isn’t populated for the rounded End VF values, causing an assertion in isScalarAfterVectorization. The population typically happens when building plans and evaluating costs for candidate VFs. To fix without touching assertions, I will ensure that when iterating with the rounded End in buildVPlansWithVPRecipes, the planner also triggers cost model analysis for each VF in the SubRange so Scalars are populated. The simplest safe change is to clamp EndRounded back to a power-of-2 boundary that matches existing cost model computations by also rounding MinVF up to the same scheme to avoid introducing unseen VFs. I will adjust MinVF similarly, rounding it down to the previous power of 2, ensuring all iterated VFs are those the cost model expects.

```bash
sed -i '9229,9232c\  auto MaxVFTimes2 = MaxVF * 2;
  auto EndRounded = ElementCount::get(llvm::NextPowerOf2(MaxVFTimes2.getKnownMinValue()), MaxVFTimes2.isScalable());
  auto StartRounded = ElementCount::get(llvm::PowerOf2Floor(MinVF.getKnownMinValue()), MinVF.isScalable());
  for (ElementCount VF = StartRounded; ElementCount::isKnownLT(VF, EndRounded);) {
    VFRange SubRange = {VF, EndRounded};' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp && sed -i 's/#include "llvm/Support/MathExtras.h"/#include "llvm/Support/MathExtras.h"/' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp && nl -ba llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp | sed -n '9226,9236p'

